14
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:09,700
Role Playing Games are not only games, they're also a form of interactive group storytelling.

15
00:01:09,700 --> 00:01:18,160
The games have rules, but within the system of rules, players can have a level of control over their persona and their actions that traditional boardgames and strategy games don't provide.

16
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:20,100
RPGs are mostly open-ended.

17
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:24,240
The rules of the game loosely manage players' choices through a series of consequences.

18
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:27,840
And the game provides an outline of the world in which the games take place.

19
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:32,880
But beyond that structure players have a lot of control over their character and their fate.

20
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:36,220
RPGs incorporate every world setting imaginable.

21
00:01:36,220 --> 00:01:40,040
You can be a knight in a medieval world filled with magic and hand-to-hand combat,

22
00:01:40,040 --> 00:01:44,360
an energized hacker in the future,
or even a werewolf in Victorian London.

23
00:01:44,360 --> 00:01:51,760
The opportunity for a player to assume an alternate persona and explore fantastic worlds is the primary appeal of a role playing game.

24
00:01:51,760 --> 00:01:57,620
And while all players have the power to change the story and outcomes of the role playing game, not all the players are created equal.

25
00:01:57,620 --> 00:02:03,120
Much of the power in an RPG is concentrated in the hands of the game master, or dungeon master.

26
00:02:03,120 --> 00:02:05,140
This is the player that runs the game.

27
00:02:05,140 --> 00:02:12,800
The GM creates the basic scenario that the rest of the players will experience and they act as the driving force behind the scenes, helping the game to progress.

28
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:17,140
They decide when enemies will appear, fight as those enemies by rolling dice behind a screen,

29
00:02:17,140 --> 00:02:22,720
act out the parts of the non-player characters encountered during the game, and determine who lives, and who dies.

30
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:29,980
The other players have to create their characters by choosing the type of hero they'll play, what equipment they'll use, and what goals their character has.

31
00:02:29,980 --> 00:02:35,600
Skills like charisma, dexterity, luck, and strength, among many others, are decided by rolling dice.

32
00:02:35,600 --> 00:02:42,260
Players also determine their character's personality and values, and will take those traits into account when the character makes decisions in the game.

33
00:02:42,260 --> 00:02:49,560
They may have to fight monsters, avoid traps, negotiate a treaty, or save a captor during each session, otherwise known as as a campaign.

34
00:02:49,560 --> 00:02:54,660
Campaigns can be customized to play out in a single evening, or they may be structured to last weeks, or months.

35
00:02:54,660 --> 00:02:58,300
Now acting has been around for thousands of years, and so have games.

36
00:02:58,300 --> 00:03:04,460
But this particular combination of drama, gaming, and imagination that constitutes RPGs, are a more recent development.

37
00:03:04,460 --> 00:03:06,860
RPGs get part of their inheritance from war gaming.

38
00:03:06,860 --> 00:03:08,680
You see this all the time in Game of Thrones.

39
00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:11,360
War gaming looks a like like John Snow's plan to take back Winterfell.

40
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:16,880
A map is unfurled across a table and covered with miniatures that represent the real forces out on the battlefield.

41
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:21,840
It's been used for centuries as a way for commanders to plan their next attack, and anticipate what the enemy will do.

42
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:25,860
Overtime this practice evolved from a serious life-or-death set of choices to a game.

43
00:03:25,860 --> 00:03:30,820
One of the earliest sets of war games was created in the now non-existent country of Prussia,

44
00:03:30,820 --> 00:03:35,500
around the start of the nineteenth century, and was named Kriegspiel, literally war game.

45
00:03:35,500 --> 00:03:40,420
It used a set of markers to represent real war forces, across a table that acted as a battlefield.

46
00:03:40,420 --> 00:03:45,220
Science fiction author H.G. Wells loves war gaming so much, he wrote the book on it.

47
00:03:45,220 --> 00:03:47,540
He published 'Little Wars' in 1915.

48
00:03:47,540 --> 00:03:54,840
The book contained a set of rules on how to use miniature figures to represent people on the battlefield, and instilled a sense of immersion and drama.

49
00:03:54,840 --> 00:04:00,700
Little Wars became a hit in 1960's America, when war gaming achieved wide popularity, particularly with American youth.

50
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:05,760
These war games focused on historic battles such as Gettysburg, and pretty much anything involving Napoleon.

51
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:10,720
At the same time, J.R.R. Tolkien's 'Lord of the Rings' novels were gaining popularity in the United States.

52
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:15,620
And the war gaming landscape shifted from recreations of real-world battles, to fantasy battles.

53
00:04:15,620 --> 00:04:21,620
This marriage of strategy war gaming and fantasy story lines would set the stage for the birth of the role playing game.

54
00:04:21,620 --> 00:04:27,520
The most successful combination of these elements, and the one that would have the biggest influence on gaming and Dungeons and Dragons.

55
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:28,600
Let's go to the Thought Bubble.

56
00:04:28,600 --> 00:04:35,640
Dungeons and Dragons, also known as D and D, set the standard for the modern RPG, and brought these games into the mainstream consciousness.

57
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:42,980
It began with two men: Gary Gygax and Dave Arneson, members of the Castles and Crusades Society a group on medieval warfare enthusiasts.

58
00:04:42,980 --> 00:04:47,640
Gygax and his friend, Jeff Perren, had come together to craft a war game called Chainmail.

59
00:04:47,640 --> 00:04:50,060
Intended to accurately simulate medieval warfare.

60
00:04:50,060 --> 00:04:54,340
In a slightly stereotypical move, it was unleashed on the world from a basement.

61
00:04:54,340 --> 00:05:00,780
Gygax founded a company in his basement and called it Tactical Studies Rules, or TSR, to help distribute their work to players.

62
00:05:00,780 --> 00:05:06,840
In the meantime, Arneson was working with fellow gamer Fred Wesley to infuse more excitement and story telling into the games.

63
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:14,900
After they played a boring round of a war game, Wesley tried to spice things up by giving each player a personal goal during the next battle, and adding a touch of story.

64
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:22,360
Arneson inadvertently added magic to the game when he was inspired by an episode for Star Trek to give his druid a phaser to blast his opponents away.

65
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:25,440
This would become the old standby spell, the lightning bolt.

66
00:05:25,440 --> 00:05:27,840
Gygax and Arneson eventually combined their ideas.

67
00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:36,560
They took Gygax's original Chainmail gaming system, and added Arneson's magic and monsters to run the first ever D and D like Roleplaying Game around 1971.

68
00:05:36,560 --> 00:05:42,040
Members on the society had come over to play an Napoleonic battle, but were surprised when the table had a castle on it.

69
00:05:42,040 --> 00:05:47,220
And instead of fighting in Poland, they found themselves in a dungeon. A new genre of gaming was born.

70
00:05:47,220 --> 00:05:55,120
Gygax and Arneson released the first edition of D&D through TSR in 1974, after being rejected by gaming company after gaming company.

71
00:05:55,120 --> 00:06:00,640
They had a slow start, but by the end of the decade, TSR was selling seven thousand copies of D&D a month.

72
00:06:00,640 --> 00:06:01,820
Thanks Thought Bubble.

73
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:05,660
But Dungeons and Dragons wasn't the only RPG to emerge in the 1970s.

74
00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:13,100
The suspiciously alliterative Tunnels and Trolls was a second modern RPG, released in 1975 by Ken St. Andre.

75
00:06:13,100 --> 00:06:16,160
Hey! And was created to be more accessible than D&D.

76
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:19,920
It also had rules for solo game play, in addition to the usual group campaigns.

77
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:27,180
Then there's Chivalry and Sorcery by Fantasy Games Unlimited -- that appeared in 1977 and was intended to be a more realistic alternative to D&D.

78
00:06:27,180 --> 00:06:31,020
Chivalry and Sorcery was the first RPG to use the term Game Master.

79
00:06:31,020 --> 00:06:37,160
Fantasy Games also introduced an RPG based on Richard Adam's beloved novel about rabbits on a dangerous journey, Watership Down.

80
00:06:37,160 --> 00:06:40,560
This game was called Bunnies and Burrows.
It's not a joke.

81
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:48,040
Bunnies and Burrows was the first game that allowed players to play as non-humanoid characters, and was the first to include detailed martial arts rules in the game.

82
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:51,620
Martial arts for rabbits. Itâ€™s like Usagi Yojimbo.

83
00:06:51,620 --> 00:07:00,300
The success of Dungeons and Dragons, and its ilk, meant the role playing games and the companies that produced them sprung up like undead skeletons rising from the ground.

84
00:07:00,300 --> 00:07:05,220
The number of players grew rapidly, and as RPGs became more widely known, they also came to be feared.

85
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:13,520
D&D appeared in a time of moral panic in the United States during the 1970s and the 80s, and RPGs recieved lots of negative media attention.

86
00:07:13,520 --> 00:07:17,720
The games were blamed for two suicides and for luring the players to satanism.

87
00:07:17,720 --> 00:07:21,360
Dr. David Waldron at the Federation University of Australia put it this way:

88
00:07:21,360 --> 00:07:30,020
"Since fantasy typically features activities like magic and witchcraft, D&D was perceived to be in direct opposition to biblical precepts and established thinking about witchcraft and magic."

89
00:07:30,020 --> 00:07:35,320
Carl Raschke, one of the leading thinkers among those who felt America was in the grips of Satan wrote:

90
00:07:35,320 --> 00:07:39,200
"D&D is really an elementary-level home study kit for 'black magic.'"

91
00:07:39,200 --> 00:07:46,200
There was even a group form in 1983 called Bothered About Dungeons and Dragons, or BADD, that launched an intense media campaign against the game.

92
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:53,800
In Harbor City Utah, 300 concerned citizens appeared at a school board meeting in 1980 to oppose the use of D&D in a school program.

93
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:56,300
One concerned citizen was quoted as saying the game,

94
00:07:56,300 --> 00:08:01,880
"is very anti-religious...these books are filled with things that are not fantasy, but are actual in the real demon world,

95
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:07,080
and can bevery dangerous for anyone involved in the game because it leaves them so open to satanic spirits."

96
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:19,380
In 1982, a TV movie called Mazes and Monsters told the chilling tale of college students drawn so deeply into the world of RPGs that one of them, played by Tom Hanks in his first leading role, was driven to suicide.

97
00:08:19,380 --> 00:08:22,240
There are a lot of 80s movies getting rebooted.
Don't do this one.

98
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:27,680
But RPGs don't actually deliver players into the grips of evil spirits, or drive them into severe mental illness.

99
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:33,080
Actually, in recent years, several studies indicate that role playing games can have many benefits for people who play them.

100
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:41,260
A case study conducted by Louise Zaya and Bradford Lewis in New York City in 1985, looked at 8 and 9 years old boys who has problems with interpersonal interaction and hyperactivity.

101
00:08:41,260 --> 00:08:46,640
"Playing D&D actually helped the boys work together and benefit from each other's strength and individual talents.

102
00:08:46,640 --> 00:08:50,080
It helped them build social skills, teamwork, and problem solving abilities."

103
00:08:50,080 --> 00:08:54,420
And a 1987 study on the emotional stability of RPG players concluded:

104
00:08:54,420 --> 00:08:59,040
"Increased exposure to D&D is not positively correlated with emotional instability.

105
00:08:59,040 --> 00:09:03,400
Indeed, as a whole group, D&D players obtain a healthy psychological profile."

106
00:09:03,400 --> 00:09:08,440
In the end, the consensus seems to be that role playing games aren't much different from other types of games.

107
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:12,780
They tend to foster connecting among the players, and important teamwork and problem solving.

108
00:09:12,780 --> 00:09:19,840
As long as you don't have a lame Dungeon Master who always changes the rules on you and injures the mage that you've been leveling up for 25 years!

109
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:26,580
Hey, I am not advocating paranoia, but maybe just ask that DM to show you the die next time they claim to role a 20.

110
